Web search results for query: "Convex database queries authentication API TypeScript examples documentation 2024"

Links: [{"title":"Queries | Convex Developer Hub","url":"https://docs.convex.dev/functions/query-functions"},{"title":"Convex | The reactive database for app developers","url":"https://www.convex.dev/"},{"title":"Convex Tutorial: A Chat App | Convex Developer Hub","url":"https://docs.convex.dev/tutorial/"},{"title":"Convex Overview | Convex Developer Hub","url":"https://docs.convex.dev/understanding/"},{"title":"Data Types | Convex Developer Hub","url":"https://docs.convex.dev/database/types"},{"title":"Authentication | Convex Developer Hub","url":"https://docs.convex.dev/auth"},{"title":"convex-helpers - npm","url":"https://www.npmjs.com/package/convex-helpers"},{"title":"Convex Docs | Convex Developer Hub","url":"https://docs.convex.dev/home"},{"title":"Storing Users in the Convex Database | Convex Developer Hub","url":"https://docs.convex.dev/auth/database-auth"},{"title":"Integrations: Integrate Convex with Clerk","url":"https://clerk.com/docs/integrations/databases/convex"}]

Based on the search results, I found comprehensive information about Convex database queries, authentication, API usage, and TypeScript examples from 2024. Here's a summary of the key findings:

## Convex Database Overview
Convex is a reactive database where you can express every part of your backend in pure TypeScript, from database schemas to queries, from auth to APIs. In Convex, your database queries are just TypeScript code written in your server functions. There is no SQL to write. There are no ORMs needed.

## Query Functions
Queries are the bread and butter of your backend API. They fetch data from the database, check authentication or perform other business logic, and return data back to the client application. 

Here's a basic query example from the documentation:
```typescript
import { query } from "./_generated/server";
import { v } from "convex/values";

// Return the last 100 tasks in a given task list.
export const getTaskList = query({
  args: { taskListId: v.id("taskLists") },
  handler: async (ctx, args) => {
    const tasks = await ctx.db
      .query("tasks")
      .filter((q) => q.eq(q.field("taskListId"), args.taskListId))
      .order("desc")
      .take(100);
    return tasks;
  },
});
```

## Authentication in Convex
Convex is compatible with most authentication providers because it uses OpenID Connect (based on OAuth) ID tokens in the form of JWTs to authenticate WebSocket connections or RPCs. These JWTs can be provided by any service (including your own Convex backend) that implement the appropriate OAuth endpoints to verify them.

For authentication checks in functions:
The most common way is to simply write code that checks if the user is logged in and if they are allowed to do the requested action at the beginning of each public function.

## TypeScript Integration Examples
Queries are TypeScript functions that can only read from the database. As we'll see in a bit, you subscribe to them from your frontend to keep your app automatically up to date.

Here's an example of a mutation with authentication:
```typescript
import { mutation } from "./_generated/server";

export const store = mutation({
  args: {},
  handler: async (ctx) => {
    const identity = await ctx.auth.getUserIdentity();
    if (!identity) {
      throw new Error("Called storeUser without authentication present");
    }
    // Check if we've already stored this identity before.
    const user = await ctx.db
      .query("users")
      .withIndex("by_token", (q) => 
        q.eq("tokenIdentifier", identity.tokenIdentifier)
      )
      .unique();
    // ... rest of logic
  },
});
```

## Client Integration
```typescript
import { useQuery } from "convex/react";
import { api } from "../convex/_generated/api";

export function MyApp() {
  const data = useQuery(api.myFunctions.sum, { a: 1, b: 2 });
  // do something with `data`
}
```

## Authentication with Clerk Integration
It's important to use the useConvexAuth() hook instead of Clerk's useAuth() hook when you need to check whether the user is logged in or not. The useConvexAuth() hook makes sure that the browser has fetched the auth token needed to make authenticated requests to your Convex backend, and that the Convex backend has validated it.

The documentation shows that Convex provides comprehensive TypeScript support with end-to-end type safety, automatic reactivity for real-time updates, and seamless integration with popular authentication providers like Clerk.

